,Recommended,310080,24499164,"Posted: 24 July, 2016",all,mattysones,"As you play the normal routes you receive clues that not everything as it seems. The characters are ACTUALLY birds, and you are ACTUALLY a human going to a Japanese bird school. This isn't played for laughs in the writing, even during the normal routes.There's no ""good end bad end"" endings but ""non-canon"" endings where, quite simply, you survive and successfully romance a bird (Except a few endings but you'll find those if you play).The BBL (Bad Boys Love): Hurtful Boyfriend ending unlocks when you've received all fourteen endings. BBL tells the canon story of the Hatoful world, explaining WHY you, Hiyoko Tosaka, are a human coexisting with highly evolved birds.It's a long convoluted story, taking approximately four hours to complete. The BBL ending plays like a normal route until about halfway through the school year, when Hiyoko is murdered.Sh*t hits the fan, and you don't have choices like a normal route. The game turns into a visual novel, only requiring you to click along to continue the dialogue and reveal the story.I think Hatoful's only real flaw (besides some typos, notably in Nageki's BBL ending) is the monotony if you're trying to unlock all the endings at once. Luckily there's a fast forward button.This is a good story. The Planet of the Apes scenario works well, and you become less concerned that this school is for birds, and more interested in the characters and why things have been a little weird this whole time. It takes dating game tropes and turns them into its own.Hatoful completely flips the direction of typical dating games, to tell a good story, and remains self-aware the whole time.I really like this game and encourage people who enjoy strong writing to play it. 10/10. Would attend birb school again."
