,Recommended,310080,33820010,Posted: 26 July,all,Uberlatios,"I saw so many positive reviews that I figured they had to be mostly joke reviews, saying the game is amazing when it's really not. Like how Birdemic has 10/10 ratings on imdb saying the film brought family members back to life.Buy holy crap, what to say about this game? I've never played anything like it. This flips the genre of dating sims on its head and makes the player expect it to be one thing, then turn out to be the exact opposite. What begins as a silly dating sim featuring birds to mix up the formula becomes a horror mystery visual novel in later playthroughs. The first ten endings you get serve to build up the world and characters while introducing small bits of a greater theme, but it is once you get ten endings that the game decides to give the player a new option for how to play the game. Do yourself a favor and choose that option.Thi is a legitimately great experience. It's humorous, insane, and in some character's routes, absolutely grand. Who is the political traitor? Are there murders or simply devious tricks all meant to confuse certain characters? And why are you, a human, attending a school for birds?The only possible complaints I can think of are that it can get incredibly text-heavy with little player input for decently long stretches at a time, and there are the occasional terrible grammatical or spelling errors that can confuse an entire sentence. You can save whenever at the click of a button, so time shouldn't discourage you from playing this. Please play this so long as you have any interest at all. It honestly won't disappoint....Seriously, how many dating sims have RPG combat? That's telling of this game's creativity. Now it's up to you to find out who or what that combat is against.Yuuya is best husbando."
76561198112059304,Recommended,310080,12019170,"Posted: 7 September, 2014",all,Pannacone,"Let's be honest: we all buy Hatoful Boyfriend for the sheer absurdity of what is, at its core, a visual novel pigeon dating game. And, on its surface at least, Hatoful Boyfriend is a shallow dating sim where the human main character is enrolled at St. PigeoNation's, a school for pigeons. She takes classes, she goes to festivals, and she romances and falls in love with various species of birds. However, Hatoful Boyfriend's stereotypical high school romance exterior is only an entertaining and light-hearted charade that covers up a plot full of politics, intrigue, mystery, and sorrow.The first half of Hatoful Boyfriend is quirky and humorous, filled with various pop culture jokes and absurd situations. Players find themselves romancing one of several standard character archetypes: the childhood best friend, the lazy professor, the haughty aristocrat, the womanizing jock, the bullied library nerd, and so on. The scenarios are cute and heart-warming, with each character having their own separate little storyline. Every short playthrough of the game—which frequently take under an hour even if you read all of the text—ends with a primarily sappy romantic ending.As players go through multiple playthroughs of Hatoful Boyfriend, however, a more insidious underlying plot is slowly revealed. Every romantic plot line will unveil more pieces of St. PigeoNation's dark history and the tragic cast of characters that attend classes there. These pieces on their own add spice to an otherwise bland dating sim that seems to cash in on its unique and somewhat ridiculous premise of a human girl dating pigeons. And, if one were to stop playing Hatoful Boyfriend after only a couple of playthroughs, that would be the feeling that one would be left with: Hatoful Boyfriend is an amusing dating game to spend an afternoon on, but nothing remarkable.However, players that choose to stop playing Hatoful Boyfriend after only a few short playthroughs are missing out on the part of Hatoful Boyfriend that makes it an excellent game. If the first thirteen playthroughs of Hatoful Boyfriend are an amusing way to pass an afternoon, then the last playthrough is a gut-wrenching ride through a twisting plot that ties together everything the player has done up to that point. The short of it is this: this isn't just a game that you should play, it's a game that you should strive to complete 100% of the way."
