,Recommended,310080,22119145,"Posted: 28 March, 2016",all,Waffle King,"♥♥♥♥ Her Right In The Cloaca-An Official Waffle King Review~Find morehere.Everyone just wants to find love in this wild, crazy world of ours. Everyone just needs a shoulder to lean on, or an open ear to whisper their darkest secrets to. That's all anyone really wants. Even the ones that don't seem like they want love, they're the ones that need it the most.Some people find love in family, or camaraderie. Some people find it in romance, or art. Some might find it at the bottom of a family-size bag of Cheetos while they jack off to pictures of girls with tails. Hey, everyone has their thing. Everyone is entitled to their own form of love. Unless they're humping their dog or their child, in which case it's illegal and they can find love in a prison shower.People can find love everywhere and anywhere. Life finds a way. Even if you must go beyond your comfort zone. Beyond your race, your culture, and your people. Love knows no limits. Not even the sky. Because who wouldn't ♥♥♥♥ a bird?I know I sure would. And if you don't think you're up to it, you haven't played this masterpiece yet. This isn't just a game. It's a journey. A life-changing experience. Prepare to have your eyes opened to the truth.Hatoful Boyfriend actually falls under the category of visual novel, as it's a Japanese otome game. Otome is Japanese for sausage fest. You're playing a girl getting aggressively humped by every guy in the immediate vicinity. Which, in this case, are all birds. And you get to make the exciting choices that will determine not only who's eggs you'll be laying, but the fate of the world as we know it.Hatoful Boyfriend was originally developed for the PC in 2011, later seeing multiple rereleases and upgrades before getting an HD remaster that released on Steam, PS4, and PS Vita.Hatoful Boyfriend is, simply by existing, worth checking out. No where else can you experience the excitement of being the only human girl at an all-birds high school. It's the only of its kind, and simply the premise itself should warrant at least a single playthrough.Not only is it relevant simply because of its premise, but it also works rather well simply on its premise alone. If you're picking it up simply because ""LOOK, BIRDS"" you'll get exactly what you're looking for. It's wacky, zany, kooky bird fun. Good stuff.But underneath that simple premise, a surprising amount of depth is layered. Spoiler alert, dating birds at an all-birds school is not something people usually do. Usually. It's not quite a mainstream way of life yet, but we're rallying for our lifestyle to be recognized by the masses. Someday, human-bird relationships might be accepted. Birds don't even have access to public schooling yet, so we have a ways to go.Shockingly, Hatoful Boyfriend is a parody dating sim. A joke game of sorts, satirizing the otome genre. All of the cliches, all of the character stereotypes, they're all here. You can expect all of basics to be here. Maid costumes and all. It's tasteful satire, not in an overbearing ""LOOK GUYS WE'RE MAKING JOKES HERE"" kind of way. The writing is hilarious, and carries a sort of ironic whimsy to it. It's fully aware of its nature, but runs with it regardless. It is a visual novel, which means reading, which means no this is not an action game or anything vigorous like that. Unless you wanna dip your little parakeet perch in honey and bird seed so you can stick it through the bars of grandma's lovebird cage while you play. Those HD character portraits are pretty feathery.It's not only poking fun at otome visual novels, it's in fact written well enough to be a competent example of the genre that it's making a mockery of. The characters are interesting and compelling in their own right, even if they are just caricatures of otome stereotypes given bird form. They're fleshed out with a surprising amount of detail, given that the nature of the game didn't require much to begin with. Just ""look, they're birds that you can date, this one is the jock bird and this one is the nerd bird"" would have sold just as well.If you happen to fall in love with the excellently written birds and words, a lot is in store for you. They've done a beyond fantastic job of rewarding the player for dedication. As a dating sim should, there are multiple endings. At least one for each character, and sometimes two. One ""true ending"" should you flawlessly woo them, and the just okay ending. Where you confess your love and they say ""thanks"". Going the extra mile for more endings will reward you by unlocking even more endings. Better endings.And should you stick around long enough for every single ending, you will be generously rewarded with the best part of the game. There's a lot of tough choices to make, but if you make them all it will be so worth it.Fantastic writing, characters, atmosphere, and a stunning amount of depth and meaning really make Hatoful stand out among other visual novel games. But it's not without issues, though they're more to blame of the genre itself than anything else.After you've played through the game for the first time, regardless of which bird you hope to woo, much of the game remains the same. You'll be going to the same classes, seeing a lot of similar dialogue, and riding the fast-forward text button a ton. That's the biggest flaw with the game.The other being, as I mentioned, the game rewarding people that stick through the game until the very end. Because it's a really big reward. Like, possibly the size of the rest of the game itself in its entirety. I can totally understand why they did it, because the reward itself doesn't carry quite the same impact and meaning until you've played through every ending. It's a steep hill to climb, with a pay-off to match.To go any further would spoil just how perfect the ending is, but it stays true to its absurdity all the way to the end. It honestly blew me away how much depth they put into it. It's really not a one-trick pigeon, as it might lead you to believe.People might dismiss it as ""that weird bird game"" or ""creepy Japanese♥♥♥♥♥♥quot; or ""memes"". They might play it purely for the ""look at me lol I'm so random"" factor, or the jack off to those luscious, feathery bodies. But you realize you're dismissing, stereotyping, and fetishizing a way of life. There's more to it than that. There's depth here. We're more than a stereotype, and I'm tired of needing to hide who I am.Educate yourself, open your mind, and accept that some people have a different lifestyle than you. Some people want to have a nice family with kids in a suburban house. They want that white picket fence life. And some people, they really like birds. Not that there's anything wrong with that. And if you think there is, I think you need to check your privilege. ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥."
