,Recommended,310080,29291554,Posted: 16 January,all,Bombshell,"Hatoful BoyfriendA game by birds, for birds, of birds.What can I even begin to say about this game? What can anyone say about this game? Is this even a game? I can't really tell much anymore.So, if it isn't blatantly obvious by the big blue thumbs-up right over there to the left a little bit, I like this game. A lot. In fact, it has surpassed, to me, the likes of Undertale, Borderlands, and my previous favourite game in existence (Pokémon Mystery Dungeon: Explorers of Sky, which I would absolutely recommend you try via emulator if you haven't played it already), to reign supreme above them all, now sitting in my second-favourite spot overall as of August 2017.Why?Well, I'm glad you asked. That's what this ""Review"" feature on Steam is for. It's a really handy little thing.TL;DR ReviewSo, first off, the short version for all of you who'd like to get a general consensus on my feelings about this game and why you should have bought it already, and then bought it for a friend or seven immediately afterwards, and for those who want to avoid knowing much about it. Trust me, you really do want to go into this game knowing as little as possible.Hatoful Boyfriend is a dating simulation game about birds. Pigeons, to be exact. It has you play the only human girl in a school full of the things, and it's your job to get one of them to like you enough to have beautiful, mutated half-bird/half-human hybrid children a couple years down the line with.Of course, you've got a wide selection to choose from. You have your typical tropes that can be found in most of these sort of visual novel-style games, such as the ""best friend"" character and the character who thinks they're above everyone else, but there's also some more varied personalities, including a creepy doctor and someone who thinks they live in a JRPG.If you're a fan of these sorts of point-and-click narrative-driven experiences, then you'll adore Hatoful Boyfriend, as it both combines a legitimately enthralling narrative with a grand amount of humour, wit, and a tendency to subvert the tropes the genre is based on.It plays great, it looks great, and if you find that you like the characters' personalities, which are the driving force of the experience, then there is not a doubt in my mind that you will find yourself having fun when going through, even if it's just for the first couple of routes you decide on. Which, by the way, there are a total of sixteen of spread out amongst the game. It's honestly pretty impressive.Alright, now that that's out of the way, please play the game before reading any further. I'm dead serious. I do not spoil anything directly other than the personalities of each individual character and a couple other minor things, but I assure you that the experience is much better suited to play absolutely on your own. Go buy it right now, sit down, get a couple endings, and come back if you so choose.Or just ignore me and keep reading. Whatever's your cup of tea.The Actual ReviewTake this as a secondary line of caution even if you don't need one, but I cannot quite fit the full review on here. Instead, I've made a Google Document containing the rest of it.If you really want to slog through all of my detailed opinions, you can do so here:https://docs.google.com/document/d/1O9psrhGKXXMgyj4W_GMLPY_5jq0LQl8koUbumt1PyM0Long story short, though, buy this game. Just do it."
