76561198219030272,Recommended,310080,28231162,"Posted: 6 December, 2016",all,WhitewoodPhantom,"Initially, Hatoful Boyfriend struck me as a purely comedic otome game. Like many who chose to play it, I decided to go through it for kicks. Eventually, I learned that it is not what it seems at all. The more I progressed through the game the more immersed I became in it. I forgot all about the fact that it was meant to be a dating simulator where you court birds. I learned that it possesses all the trappings of classic visual novels. It is rife with plot twists and angst. The story is surprisingly deep, something I found to be a relief. As you go through the routes you obtain more and more pieces of the proverbial puzzle. They fit together pretty nicely at the end. I was glad to know that it is more than just some silly thing.Although it has many elements and troupes that are common in such games it presented them in a unique way, I think. However, my taste for it was admittedly acquired. After having went through a route in its entirety I became bored of many of the jokes and scenarios which had been scattered throughout it. For a time it was a bit of a chore to go through. Thankfully, the skip button helps you rush through the things you have already read, cutting out unnecessary game-time. You definitely need to be patient when going through Hatoful Boyfriend. I personally feel that in order to get the most enjoyment out of it you should go through one route at a time. That way you will have plenty of time to reflect on what happened as well as keep your interest in the plot fresh.PROS:> Overall, Hatoful Boyfriend is short and sweet. A basic route can be finished in an hour even if you are a slow reader. This makes it a great thing to play before going to bed or when you just need to kill some time for a while.> The art is soft, and the scenery colorful, making the backdrops pleasant. It is simple, but is still able to add to the mood.> While many of the characters and their stories are tried-and-true they are still ones you can get attached to (for the most part, anyway).> There is more than one unlockable route.> The story becomes more advanced as you progress through the game.CONS:> The protagonist is simple and impressionable.> During the main routes you do not get a lot of route-exclusive content. A lot of the scenarios are the ones you go through during the main story, so you end up having to read through much of what you already have.> The running gags get old fast.> You are unable to save at decision screens and must do so just before you are about to make a choice.> There are very few CGs.> Sometimes your saves will bring you to a backdrop and you cannot do anything at all so you have to exit and re-open the game (save your game in multiple slots just in case!).All in all, I think that Hatoful Boyfriend is enjoyable. I feel that it rewards you well for your diligence. The final, true story that is Hatoful Boyfriend is great. I absolutely love the BBL ending, and think that it was worth all the time I spent working to get it. I believe that it is a fairly solid purchase."
,Recommended,310080,12579947,"Posted: 20 October, 2014",all,•SADBOY•,"Awe, this was a cute game. Very short though, unless you go through all of the endings. My first playthrough i got the Kazuaki ending. I bought it for the birds, but it was actually really good. I had the human portraits enabled. This would have been a nice story even if it had been humans. Probably wouldn't attract much attention like it does now. 10/10."
