76561198078564933,Recommended,310080,14090547,"Posted: 20 January, 2015",all,Celtic Rose,"I bought the Collector's Edition so I will do a small review of the game and a look over the extras you get.I love visual novels and when I first got this game I thought it was going to be a very sweet but quite gimmicky. I played the demo on the original site and boy was I wrong. Yes the game can indeed be very sweet but it can also be very dark. The game had a depth and was so well written that I had never expected. Now I will say I have played LOADS of visual novel games and am very finicky about which ones I buy. The moment this game came to Steam I bought it the first moment I noticed it was there.Its well written, the characters are well developed and believeable (with the exception of Okasan and Aghel but that's how they are supposed to be), the music is lovely and well fitted to the areas they are used, it had multiple endings which depended on your stats in some cases, you actually LEARN the birds names which were chosen to represent the men you can be with in this game and its just engrossing. The game itself is a definite recommend.Now I will look at the extra you get with Hatoful Boyfriend Collectors Edition:It comes with the soundtrack which as I said its a lovely soundtrack and it seems to include all of the songs.The wallpapers was disappointing. It just came with two wallpapers featuring the purple heart background and fantail pigeons.The comic is short but sweet. Each character has two mini comics (4 frames) after them. It doesn't add to the story in any way its just quite sweet. Though there was only one that made me laugh.The yearbook. I will say this now its not a yearbook. Its actually just a virtual artbook made to look like a yearbook which disappointed me greatly. I hoped it would be Tosaka's year book with pictures of her class inside and signed with a message from each of the main characters but no such luck. The art work is quite nice but not what I was expecting.The actual game is definitely worth a buy but the collector's edition I'd advise you only get if it was on offer for a £1 or two (three if you really want it) Its not worth its £5 price tag."
,Recommended,310080,16577149,"Posted: 21 June, 2015",all,Gabriel Riley,"So far I've only unlocked 3 endings, but I also got the ""Bad Ending"" (and its achievement)! Jeez. It's simple and easy to read, and once you know the main arc you can hammer your mouse through it to get to new content for new boyfriends really fast.High Points:-The story is interesting and there's no shortage of drama, for sure (If you came for anything else in a dating sim, you're in the wrong place).-Lots of variation! My favorite birdie is Yuuya, but I don't think I have a least favorite. They're all super fun and creatively designed.-This game keeps surprising me.Low Points:-There probably won't be a lot of replayability :/-Yuuya's romance was hard to figure out; I got the Bad Ending just trying the first go around, and Ryouta fell in love with me the second time. I ended up looking up the first couple steps to get myself on the right track. I also have no idea how to romance Azumi. This game gives you goals and no instruction manual!-The soundtrack kind of bothers me. It doesn't fade or change evenly, but stops abruptly when scenes shift or ends when a scene times out (I left my computer for a while and came back and the game was absolutely silent). That's par for the course for a lot of dating sims though.If you like anime pigeons and you need something for a quiet evening in, this is a good filler :o) each romance only takes about 30-45 minutes. 8/10"
