,Recommended,310080,15917173,"Posted: 20 May, 2015",all,KumoriRaven,"""Ha, pigeons? How weird. Let's buy this game, just for fun."" Most people say this before purchasing this game. I know. I did in 2012 when it first came out on another website. I bought the game and decided to go for the most familiar bird to me. The Mourning Dove, Nageki.A young boy who died too young. He was put in a medical centre because of his weak immune system. He had a disease, the H5N1 virus. It was able to kill the humans that killed Nageki's family. However, he didn't want to kill the humans. He said he couldn't live anymore, so he threw himself into the fire he lit in the centre's basement.This game turned sad when I reached his ending. I decided to replay it, this time going for the fluffball of a partridge, Shuu, or shall I sayIsa Souma.His ending made this game much darker. I decided to play the rest of the game. After I played Ryouta's ending, a new choice popped up.I could fulfill a promise. I didn't know it at the time, but I wasn't Hiyoko when I made the choice. I was the Doctor. Shuu wanted to fulfill the promise he made to someone he loved. The game switched genres before my eyes. It went from a supposedly silly dating simulator to a horrifying murder mystery with pigeons.This game, while being amazing, has a few flaws, but they are quite small compared to the pros. The grammar isn't very good compared to some games, but what do you expect from a game translated into English from Japanese. There are also numerous plot holes that aren't solved unless you buy the sequel, Holiday Star. Likewhy Hitori bleached his feathers. Most believe that it was to hide his true identity to get revenge on Shuu. While that is true, there is a second reason.Overall, this game is fantastic. It gets you hooked on the eerie and sad twists and then just makes a 360 turn into pigeon hell. There is no escaping now.Rating8 running Okosan's out of 10."
