,Recommended,310080,12918739,"Posted: 12 November, 2014",all,JakkelR4psc4llion,"Hatoful Boyfriend is a visual novel video game about a high-school age Japanese human girl who lives in a cave and attends a very prestigious prep school for pigeons. Very early on, the game offers you the option to see ""human portrait"" versions of every male pigeon when you meet them and from there on, you must decide which pigeon to date. With that all in mind, believe me when I say that this game will suprise you with just how insane it is, and I love it all the more for that reason (among others).My first introduction to the genre of Japanese visual novels was with Sakura Spirit, and that really only had tons of fan-service and an adorable story about cute yet desperately horny furries and their friends. While I enjoyed the fan-service, I felt Sakura Spirit was pretty hollow as a visual novel as it only gave the player one choice to make in the entire game. So when it came time for me to give Hatoful Boyfriend a try, I was hooked immediately by the web of choices waiting to be discovered in the game. Where Sakura Spirit had a single choice that would only partially change the game, Hatoful Boyfriend has a string of multiple reactions that will end up in different endings. Where Sakura Spirit had badly translated sensuality and fanservice, Hatoful Boyfriend has full blown insanity with extremely well-written plot twists. The only other game I've played where I was this desperate to replay the game in hopes of seeking out different endings was the Stanley Parable, and believe me when I say that this game is so much more worthy of a multiple ending gag game.While the premise and initial setting for the game is pretty absurd and quirky, you are given several indications through gameplay of what type of world you live in that condones human-pigeon relationships and are given several possible endings, depending on which male bird you choose and HOW you choose them (i.e. submissively, dominantly, romantically, accidentally, etc.). Some of these endings range from the sad, to the silly, to the absurd, to the horrific, to the gut-wrenchingly insane (the ""Fallen Anghel"" ending blew my mind), to the downright non-canon. Like so many other visual novels and multi-ending video games, Hatoful Boyfriend's appeal lies in discovering each new ending and all the options hidden away in the game. Overall, the music is fitting, the translation is superb and the risk of actually dying all give the game that much more appeal.If you like insane Japanese exports, visual novels, bizarre stories of interspecies love and the support/shame it gives rise to  or a combination of all three of these things than you should definitely check out Hatoful Boyfriend!100% COMPLETION EDIT: I just finished playing the final ending. The game definitely gets deeper and darker the more endings you uncover. It make start out silly, cute and quirky, but it gets pretty grim. Very well-written, though.YEARS LATER EDIT: Yep, still a great game."
