76561198051763384,Recommended,310080,28965590,Posted: 2 January,all,Skoop,"Hatoful Boyfriend;A game where you're a human girl whom apparently has an affinity for the avian variety!Before I begin, I beg you to ignore the less informed reviews. Surely those who've dipped their toes in the water may know that, yes, indeed this water is very wet, but only those who've dived in can describe the tresures hidden beneath the surface.This game surely isn't for everyone.All in all, it IS a visual novel. The largest amount of ""gameplay"" you'll ever run into would happen to be a few faux RPG fight sequences that could hardly be taken seriously. This whole game took a lot of effort to sell me on. I'd been prowling the marketplace for months debating the price and eventually settled during a sale.Actually, I consider this game to be split into two segments that differ drastically: The dating segment and theHurtfulsegment.The first segment happened to be the more tedious portion. Our main goal is to pick a bird you are aiming to participate in a little fowl play with and pick all the moves necessary to cater to their interests. A typical visual novel in terms of dating. However, the stats tend to play a large role in HOW you progress and what endings you achieve. Certain characters have certain endings that are achieved by simply honing all your extra classes into upgrading one stat.Dating happens to be the brightest, stereo-typical, schmaltzy part of the game hence why I originally dived in this game as a joke. The blame of why dating happens to be so teeth grindingly annoying when you play this game is placed on the factTHE SAVE MECHANIC IS FAULTY.Nine times out of ten, your save will not load properly forcing you to exit the entire game and restart from the beginning.Having to restart entirely becomes moreso apparent when you have certain characters with multiple endings. Going through the entire game again.Ain't. Fun.This makes getting all the endings and unlocking the second portion of the game a test on patience. The novelty wears out quick after seeing Okosan introduce himself typical juggernaut style for the fifteenth freaking time in two hours.It's not a wonder most people wouldn't make it past the first segment, but with a little perserverence, ibuprophen and a nice guide, you unlock the meat and all it's fixins.The second portion is where this game honestly shines in story. The gameplaysags terribly here,but it wasn't something you'd miss after the trek to this point anyway. Trust me when I say that this portion of the game is wherethat entire kawaii, ha-ha nice joke facade is crumbled into little pieces then obliterated into dust. This portion is dark both atmospherically and aesthetically. The pallet dims to a much creepier violet tone and you know things get serious when this game brings out the worst.The second portion is what really reeled me in. It was this game's saving grace for me.I remember the moment everything clicked in my head, I drew back in shock. And I loved every second of it.However, in the end, things turned outbetter than I thought they would.I misjudged a lot of characters, a lot of things changed and I felt satisfied with a majority of it.I wasn't happy on their dark horse they decided to needed some phoenix down for kicks, though. I was not a happy camper.Will I ever play this game again? Not on my own time.For a stream, there is potential, but the replayability is fleeting.Overall I give this a 7/10, 3.5/5"
