,Recommended,310080,30249950,Posted: 28 February,all,Selenography,"Bought it expecting lame puns and not much else. Seven hours later and I'm contemplating getting the DLC. How did this happen to me? How do you even review this game? Even without the bizarre premise, it isn't exactly your ordinary dating VN. Hatoful Boyfriend honestly deserves plaudits just for skirting the blender of meme-game shovelware with a setting like this, let alone producing a convincingly authentic VN with a twist.Let's get it out of the way. Yes, you are a human at a school for birds. The only human. You'd expect this to be handwaved and rarely referred to, right? Bzzzt, wrong. The plot is actually far deeper than anticipated; the real cherry atop this game is the BBL route at the end, which radically alters the tone and veers in a far darker direction than the main game. Themes include: murder, suicide, rejection, dystopia, genocide and human experimentation. Yeah. Seriously grim at times, it manages to combine Sherlock and Under the Dome in fleshing out the main cast far beyond where the main game takes them.Before all that, the main game is actually pretty pleasant. The...birds...are characterised surprisingly deftly, and avoiding the common VN pitfall of nailing one identifiable trait to a character and bludgeoning you over the head with it at every opportunity. These guys are genuinely sympathetic, and each route generally avoids too much repetition beyond the first semester. Your avatar is pretty funny, and seems to channeling her inner Mongol about half the time, as she studies in class and makes choices regarding the secret lives of birds. The foreshadowing for the final route is subtly done.Even if the Bad Boys Love route didn't exist, I'd still be rating this positively...it's a solid VN, funny and polished. The end route only elevates Hatoful Boyfriend considerably above most peers, and was a refreshing departure from the usual themes in dating sims. A murder-mystery whodunnit tacked onto a game about romancing pigeons - why not?"
