,Recommended,310080,32939737,Posted: 28 June,all,WHy,"It's ridiculous how fast you get attached to these birds, and it's an experience everybody should try at least once. The story really comes into its own when you start the true route, so be sure to play to the very end."
,Recommended,310080,18564856,"Posted: 19 October, 2015",all,Bakeneko,"TL;DR: My favorite visual novel game, period. I consider it a must-play for VN/otome fans.---Overall Impression: It took me awhile to get past, ""Oh, Japan... dating birds?"" to try it out. I had resolved I'd heard enough to give it a go, but it took watching Dodger's (presshearttocontinue) Let's Play to actually buy it. It made me laugh and it made me genuinely cry. It's probably best if you are familiar with otome game tropes, but a good background in anime/manga might do to pick up on all the jokes. Even if you only come at the game for the ""weirdness"", I hope you stay to see its real charm.Content: Don't get me wrong - Hatoful Boyfriend may be silly and weird and cute on the surface and once you dig past it, well, it'sstillsilly and weird... But it also brushes along some really dark and heavy stuff. The list that follows will contain content spoilers, though if you have issues, it's better to have mild spoilers than be upset.SPOILERS: There is violence. Death - lots of death. War. Genocide. Murder (including of children). Suicide.Translation: I think the translation is fantastic.Editing: A few very minor issues, but overall, I had no complaints. I can't even remember any specific issues.Art: Let's get real here... there's really not a lot of ""art"" here! Unlike many VNs, there are no ""event"" CGs. Each character really gets one sprite with no changes of expression and the human portrait you see onceifyou turn on the human portrait option. In the end, it honestly adds to the absurdity, so I have no complaints. The backgrounds are pretty gorgeous, though. And the ending slates are really cute. The artist has done comics with the gang and sometimes does artwork of the characters, which she posts to her Tumblr and Deviantart accounts. If you want art, check those things out, because they're great!Story: On the surface, you're sold on, ""Oh, Japan!"" - just the absurd premise of a human girl going to a school for intelligent birds and falling in love with one of the birdie boyfriends available in typical ""school romance"" style.You dig a little deeper and you see the tropes being made fun of (gently, and with love).Then you start caring about these ""dumb birds"".Then you're hit with something heavy. If you get to the point of caring, it's pretty much guaranteed it'll hurt. The author skillfully manipulates you to this point and I admire her greatly for it.I honestly find myself at a loss to describe the story in any other way. I don't really see the birds as ""bachelors to be wooed"", though technically they are. They are, however, characters to fall in love with, and I do. I love every one of them, faults and all.The Heroine: She's kind of a meathead, honestly! (The creator also uses a cartoon piece of meat to represent her in the comics.) She's weird and maybe not entirely bright on the surface - but she's probably much smarter than she lets on. She definitely has a personality of her own! (She just has no official character design!) There's something subversive about her that the more I get to know her, the more I appreciate her.In closing...I really, really hope you pick it up. I enjoyed it enough I own the Collector's Edition (something I wouldn't necessarily recommend at full price unless you're already a fan - the comic and yearbook aren't that many pages). I also own all the comics and the sequel game, Holiday Star, from purchasing them from the creator's homepage. I'll also be purchasing a new copy of Holiday Star when it it comes to Steam. I'm a super fan! Complete with fanart! It's often on discount, but even at full price is cheap for such a great game.EDIT: Just adding that Holiday Star is out on Steam and I hope you pick it up too!"
