,Recommended,310080,18282434,"Posted: 1 October, 2015",all,ssbizznitch,"I believe I either got this game in a humble bundle or steam sale. Either way, I expected nothing more than a dumb, silly, lighthearted bird-dating sim. Oh jeez, this game was more than that.Following the routes of each bird is pretty short and nothing too special. The dialogue gets silly, and it appears to be exactly what I expected, aside from two very entertaining dating paths (Oko-San's and Anghel's).However, wooing enough of the birds unlocks the ""BBL ending"" which provides an entertaining story that has nothing to do with flirting, and everything to do with character development - and with content that is dark, twisted, and answers some of the questions left by playing through the dating paths. I finished this plot somewhere between two / two and a half hours, and it was worth it. Unlike the individual dating paths, which tend to gloss over the characters and sometimes leave unsatisfying endings, the BBL plot throws a ton of additional background story into each character, a bunch of twists, and is written well enough to make you want to finish playing through it. The BBL plot plays more as an interactive story than a sim, but for a few bucks I'd say it's worth it.Overall, the 'preliminary game' is alright but nothing too special, and each path is quite short. The BBL plotline is great and makes it worth playing through to unlock."
,Not Recommended,310080,18173811,"Posted: 24 September, 2015",all,Allthegoodnamestaken,"It has its momements, but there aren't enough of them to justify $10. Some of the main endings are funny, but you have to trudge through the same year 7 times to see them all, with *many* events repeating each time and a skip function that doesn't stop for unread text. They take 15-30 minutes each depending on your use of said skip button, and several are obnoxiously set up so that you have to go back and do everything again (but only veeeery slightly differently) in order to get a second version of the ending that's exactly the same except that it cuts to the credits earlier.And doing that is actually necessary to see everything - the final ending doesn't unlock until you've seen the other 13. That ending has the most to offer in terms of storytelling, but it drags on for far, far, longer than it ever needed to because of an obsession with repeatedly retelling the same events from perspectives that are minimally different. I started out thinking it was the highlight of the game and really should've been there from the start, but by the end I was just mashing space to make it end. There weren't any repurcussions to that approach, because this part of the game is also completely impossible to lose and provides zero choices with any impact over the course of two hours. That branch desperately needed an editor, and not just because of length - there's one part that has a sentence so badly mistranslated that it's completely meaningless.I really wish I could recommend this - I normally love dumb things that wear their stupidity as a badge of honor - but HB ruins itself by simultaneously being too short to feel meaningful and too long for the joke to stay funny. On sale, it's probably worthwhile to see an ending or two, (again, a few of the main ones are legitimately funny) but there's just not enough here for $10. It isn't bad, but I was much more entertained by reading about the original version years ago than I was actually playing the remake. Oh well."
