,Recommended,310080,16480742,"Posted: 17 June, 2015",all,Alex (Mighty Big Weeb),"A fateful evening, the day after we'd spent about two hours around a friend's house, for one specific goal: get as far into Shuu's ending of Hatoful Boyfriend as possible. And so, this date - the afterward of the events that occured - is where we begin, upon a fateful evening where the sunlight is still nigh and I am attempting to write a script for Drama class.I'm looking on Steam with curiosity - could Hatoful Boyfriend be featured on the Summer Sale? A loud gasp escapes my throat and echoes into the distance of the obstacle course-like living room, startling my mother. Indeed, the beloved game in which you can date different species of birds is on sale: for £1.74? This is my chance. It is normally £6.99 and my mother would doubt purchasing such a game. But a dating game about pigeons for £1.74...She requests something before granting me the game and her honest endless respect. My mother looks at me with disrespect, wondering why her fourteen-year-old daughter is playing a dating game - about birds, nonetheless? Ah, she must think that I am insane! It is my goal now to become connected to these birds, draw myself closer to them, bring my life towards them. My mother was correct. This game is the game of an insane man and she is as correct as the daylight's honestly scolding sunlight. We are insane. As our feelings for birds develop all that we desire is indeed the fact that we are human, much like our fated protagonist of HB (inc. Hurtful Boyfriend) and will eventually fall in love with birds, the dominant species when bird flu overtakes. Pray that we will be the few who are immune to the bird flu and we remain as human as possible. It may seem bizarre, but it is simply humane, in our eyes. We do not love humans any more. It is birds all around for each other, one another, and that is how it will remain.We will woo the birds until we are exhausted and our wings will form. Our wings of freedom. Our wings of responisibility. Our wings that defeat all other love unless it regards birds."
