,Recommended,310080,17918723,"Posted: 6 September, 2015",all,Merlin the Tuna,"Hatoful Boyfriend takes a fun one-note gag of dating birds and executes it flawlessly, then executes half a dozen other things flawlessly while it's at it. It constantly mixes up its approach, and the result is a story that manages to be hilarious, goofy as all hell, but also legitimately touching.Ultimately, playing Hatoful is something of a question of sincerity. Yes, the world and story are totally bananas. But the game's willingness to change tone on a dime and play things completely straight leads to no small number of poignant moments. The world of St. Pigeonation's is absurd, but is it really any more absurd than the latest tale of heroic space marines, robo-Nazis, or godlike gangsters? Not really, and at some point, after dealing with characters that act, talk, hope, and fear just like people, you're going to stop caring that their portrait is a ridiculous looking bird. And then, just when you start to get a little emotional, it's going to hit you in the face with another pie.If there's a downside, it's that the actual gameplay can get a little tedious. A huge chunk of the game doesn't open up until you've romanced all of the birds, and a few of the birds have ""normal"" vs. ""perfect"" endings that make for two near-identical playthroughs. So after a few times through, you'll want to pull up a guide (and thankfully there are some good ones) and make judicious use of the fast-forward button to breeze through repeat content. I promise it's worth it, though."
