,Recommended,310080,12792343,"Posted: 4 November, 2014",all,befaulkner,"subtly funny, but could have used more days and character development for the person you play as. I bought this expecting it to have more a sim feel to it. Also, I understand the names are Japanese but every time I read one I honestly can't remember which bird it related too. Something as simple as including a picture of their face next to the name in the menu would have made this game more accessible to me. That being said, its a wonderful concept that I've be curious about forever and I'm glad I picked it up on sale. I got clues about the back story from the first play through, but had to go to the internet to figure out what was really going on. I'd love to see this redone with gender roles switched. Anyways, thanks for reading."
,Recommended,310080,12822500,"Posted: 6 November, 2014",all,ApocaLiz,"So far this game has been one the strangest gaming experiences of my life, but also one of the most intriguing. I have only uncovered 4 of 12 possible endings, so I am nowwhere near done (as I definitely plan to uncover them all), but already it has transpired that the story is a lot more complex and nuanced than I was led to believe in my first playthrough.I have never played any dating sims, so I can't compare it to any other games in the genre, but I imagine it is already vastly different from the bulk of the genre by virtue of being about human-bird relationships. Which isn't nearly as creepy as it sounds, believe it or not. The characterizations of the different birds (and thus romance options) are surprisingly complex and   feature well put-together twists. I can't wait to find out what the next one has in store.I am also beginning to believe that one has to play all of the different paths in the game to fully understand the story. Each playthrough takes only about 30-40 minutes, so this is completely doable. Some endings appear to only be available after a couple of PTs, which further increases replayability.The music is also worth mentioning. Each character has their own theme that usually plays while the main character is having any interaction with them, and it consists of a wide variety of tunes, some known, some, I presume, specifically written for the game. Given the game's complete lack of voice acting, the music is a great way to give the characters some ""audible personality"".To sum it up, even if you are not a fan of visual novels or dating sims, this game is worth it for the incredibly strange setting and the great charactererization alone."
,Recommended,310080,12823630,"Posted: 6 November, 2014",all,Cheeriope,"At first glance this game seems ridiculous. Maybe that is what makes it all the more amazing.The story is extremely entertaining, dark, and ties things up really well. If you only play through one or two of the romances you won't get to see the really nitty gritty this game has to offer. For example: Though Okosan may make you  laugh, it really isn't as great as romancing Shuu.It took me 6 hours to get to the very end (which is unlocked after getting all 14 other endings, so it's quite long. If you do plan to beat the whole thing I would suggest doing Sukuya and Okosan first as they are, arguably, the least interesting. There is one other that isn't interesting but I'm worried it's a spoiler so I won't say it.I feel those that rate this poorly didn't take it seriously, which is a real shame. If you've every played 999 or the follow up Zero Escape for the story, not the puzzles, you will like this! Those games are rated very well because people actually took them seriously.It may have pigeons you date, but that really isn't what this game is at its core. It's the cheerful makeup the sad clown wears before he murders your family."
