,Recommended,310080,21800061,"Posted: 12 March, 2016",all,Boi,"This game, man. This bloody game.Never before had I thought a game where the main objective is to date a bird would be so engrossing.The characters are a likeable blend of personalities, from flamboyant to caring, to silly and dramatic, and everything in between. The story, which at first seemed simple, became very interesting, and even pretty dark in some places, with a great mix of absurdity and humour mixed in, as if Boris Johnson on every drug imaginable decided to contribute to the game after playing too much Final Fantasy and ate too much pudding. The music was nice and charming, and the multiple endings definately added quite a bit of replay value. The game WAS rather short, but, in all honesty, I feel like it was the right amount of short. It didn't drag on, and something usually interesting was going on in St. Pigeonations.And the final storyline, oh god, the final storyline... It was something else, let me tell ya.There's a pretty big spoiler for the final- and main, might I add- storyline of the game here, so skip if you don't want your virgin eyeballs assaulted by spoilers and such.The ""Hurtful Boyfriend"" chapter was very enjoyable, with many story twists that present themselves within this portion of the game, such as the real identity of Sakuya, the secret of what the main protagionist's role was, the tragic backstory of Nageki and Kazuyaki, the true role of Shuu, and so much more. And the whole Danganronpa vibe it gave off was so nostalgic to me, as I have played both Trigger Happy Havoc and Goodbye Despair before. I smiled the whole way through, just enjoying the feel and the story of that final story.In short, if you have the cash, buy this game. that's all I can say, really. This game is one of those examples where you shouldn't judge a book by it's cover."
