,Recommended,310080,28143329,"Posted: 2 December, 2016",all,darksiren,"What really gets me about this game isn't the whole thing about dating birds, but that this game is incredibly dark once you get underneath the cute otome surface. It's those hints of darkness in the setting's recent past that keep me playing even through the less appealing parts (some cheesiness, predictable angst, and Okosan... ugh, I do not like San.)One thing I appreciate is that Hatoful Boyfriend doesn't try to convince you that characters that are unlikable and/or creepy ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥s are appealing love interests. You pursue them for the sake of game completion, knowing full well that your character's getting into something unappealing and possibly even dangerous. In some cases you might be surprised at what you find out. So you keep doing it anyway.I've played otome where you're wooing some misogynistic jerk or antisocial personality, and you're supposed to believe you'd actually willingly fall for that for the off chance he might turn out having some redeemable quality or sympathetic sob story. I can't stand that.I like Hatoful Boyfriend--but keep in mind, the only other otome I've played that I liked was Idea Factory's Hakuoki, a game based on Japan's Meiji era where the members of the Shinsengumi basically become vampires to avoid their historical deaths. And yes, you romance them. It's glorious!"
